SIMPLE: seed
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seed
<hw>Seed</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Seed</plw> or <plw>Seeds</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE.
<ets>seed</ets>, <ets>sed</ets>, AS. <ets>s⟦aemac⟧d</ets>, fr.
<ets>s⟦amac⟧wan</ets> to sow; akin to D. <ets>zaad</ets> seed, G.
<ets>saat</ets>, Icel. <ets>s⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, <ets>sae⟦edh⟧i</ets>,
Goth. mana<ets>s⟦emac⟧⟦thorn⟧s</ets> seed of men, world. See
<er>Sow</er> to scatter seed, and cf. <er>Colza</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A ripened ovule, consisting of an
embryo with one or more integuments, or coverings; <as>as, an apple
<ex>seed</ex>; a currant <ex>seed</ex>.</as> By germination it produces
a new plant.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any small seedlike fruit, though it
may consist of a pericarp, or even a calyx, as well as the seed proper;
<as>as, parsnip <ex>seed</ex>; thistle <ex>seed</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God said, Let the earth bring forth grass, the herb yielding
<qex>seed</qex>, and the fruit tree yielding fruit after his kind, whose
<qex>seed</qex> is in itself.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The seed proper has an outer and an inner coat, and
within these the kernel or nucleus. The kernel is either the embryo
alone, or the embryo inclosed in the albumen, which is the material for
the nourishment of the developing embryo. The scar on a seed, left where
the stem parted from it, is called the <xex>hilum</xex>, and the closed
orifice of the ovule, the <xex>micropyle</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The generative fluid of the
male; semen; sperm; -- not used in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That from which anything springs; first principle;
original; source; <as>as, the <ex>seeds</ex> of virtue or
vice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The principle of production.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Praise of great acts he scatters as a <qex>seed</qex>,⟦br⟧
<qex>Which may the like in coming ages breed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Progeny; offspring; children; descendants; <as>as,
the <ex>seed</ex> of Abraham; the <ex>seed</ex> of David</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense the word is applied to one person, or to
any number collectively, and admits of the plural form, though rarely
used in the plural.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Race; generation; birth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of mortal <qex>seed</qex> they were not held.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seed bag</b></col> <fld>(Artesian well)</fld>, <cd>a
packing to prevent percolation of water down the bore hole. It consists
of a bag encircling the tubing and filled with flax seed, which swells
when wet and fills the space between the tubing and the sides of the
hole.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed bud</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the germ
or rudiment of the plant in the embryo state; the ovule.</cd> --
<col><b>Seed coat</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the covering of a
seed.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Seed corn</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Seed grain</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>corn or grain
for seed.</cd> -- <col><b>To eat the seed corn</b></col>, <cd>To eat the
corn which should be saved for seed, so as to forestall starvation; -- a
desparate measure, since it only postpones disaster.</cd>
<specif>Hence:</specif> <cd>any desparate action which creates a
disastrous situation in the long-term, done in order to provide
temporary relief.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed down</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>the soft hairs on certain seeds, as cotton seed.</cd> --
<col><b>Seed drill</b></col>. <cd>See 6th <er>Drill</er>, 2
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed eater</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any finch of the genera <gen>Sporophila</gen>, and
<gen>Crithagra</gen>. They feed mainly on seeds.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed
gall</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any gall which resembles a seed,
formed on the leaves of various plants, usually by some species of
Phylloxera.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed leaf</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
cotyledon.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed lobe</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
cotyledon; a seed leaf.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed oil</b></col>, <cd>oil
expressed from the seeds of plants.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed
oyster</b></col>, <cd>a young oyster, especially when of a size suitable
for transplantation to a new locality.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed
pearl</b></col>, <cd>a small pearl of little value.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Seed plat</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Seed
plot</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the ground on which seeds are sown, to
produce plants for transplanting; a nursery.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed
stalk</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the stalk of an ovule or seed; a
funicle.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed tick</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>one
of several species of ticks resembling seeds in form and color.</cd> --
<col><b>Seed vessel</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>that part of a
plant which contains the seeds; a pericarp.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed
weevil</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous small
weevils, especially those of the genus <gen>Apion</gen>, which live in
the seeds of various plants.</cd> -- <col><b>Seed wool</b></col>,
<cd>cotton wool not yet cleansed of its seeds.</cd> <mark>[Southern
U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seed
<hw>Seed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sow
seed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shed the seed.</def>
<rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To grow to maturity, and to produce seed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many interests have grown up, and <qex>seeded</qex>, and twisted
their roots in the crevices of many wrongs.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Seed
<hw>Seed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Seeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Seeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sprinkle with
seed; to plant seeds in; to sow; <as>as, to <ex>seed</ex> a
field</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cover thinly with something scattered; to
ornament with seedlike decorations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sable mantle <qex>seeded</qex> with waking eyes.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To seed down</b></col>, <cd>to sow with grass
seed.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seedbox</ent>⟦br⟧
